                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="21035" author="chrislee" created="Wed, 22 Nov 2006 13:24:46 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Not sure how this is any more of a security vulnerability than submitting the password in the first place; if you&apos;ve addressed the transport security (HTTPS), then what is contained in the payload (HTTP/HTML) is encrypted to/from the browser.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="21071" author="tortuga" created="Mon, 27 Nov 2006 07:29:48 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Because of on-disk file caching. Some browsers cache HTTPS to disk. Also, what if the user saved the html to a file? Finally, what if the user leaves their browser window open and walks away from their desk? The users password is then easily retrievable. We have to protect users from themselves.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="21306" author="ojs" created="Thu, 14 Dec 2006 01:14:22 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;At least there should be an attribute for disabling the current behaviour.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="21351" author="springboy" created="Tue, 19 Dec 2006 07:55:15 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;HI all&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I have addressed this issue inline with Tor Tuga&apos;s comments. The Spring &amp;lt;password/&amp;gt; tag now no longer renders it&apos;s value... ever. This is to my mind in keeping with the fit purpose of a password input field, be it web page or rich client.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If you really do want to have this behavior be configurable (i.e. with an attribute, as per Oliver Siegmar&apos;s comment), then do feel free to reopen the issue.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Cheers&lt;br/&gt;
Rick&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="21821" author="mraible" created="Fri, 19 Jan 2007 05:45:51 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;This change breaks backwards-compatibility, which is a shame. I&apos;d like to see this tag to have an attribute that allows showing/hiding the value.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Struts 2 uses a &quot;showPassword&quot; attribute to control whether a password is displayed or not.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://struts.apache.org/2.x/docs/password.html&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;http://struts.apache.org/2.x/docs/password.html&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="21823" author="springboy" created="Fri, 19 Jan 2007 07:57:13 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Will add attribute to control the rendering of the password value for the next release.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="21827" author="springboy" created="Fri, 19 Jan 2007 23:35:05 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Sorted.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The password tag now supports a &apos;showPassword&apos; attribute, which if set to true will cause the password value to be rendered.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The password tag itself still defaults to &lt;b&gt;not&lt;/b&gt; displaying the password value.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="21906" author="tortuga" created="Thu, 25 Jan 2007 04:22:07 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Sounds perfect. Thanks Rick.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
